entry.title: picture-in-picture: Add PictureInPictureOcclusionTracker
entry.content:
This CL adds a PictureInPictureOcclusionTracker, which keeps track of

picture-in-picture widgets and widgets that need to know when they're

occluded by a picture-in-picture window, and notifies observers when

the occlusion state changes.



This will be used to ensure that security-sensitive UI does not get

covered up by a picture-in-picture window, which would leave the user

vulnerable to spoofing.



This CL just adds the tracker, but does not register any

picture-in-picture widgets to it nor any observers.

entry.title: [Passwords] Refactor sync-account-getting helper functions to unify
entry.content:
No expected behavioral differences, although strictly speaking

SyncService::GetAccountInfo() isn't guaranteed to be identical to

the account determined by IdentityManager, specially during

transitional states (e.g. in the process of signing out).



The general idea with this patch is that two functions in the same

file, password_sync_util.h, were almost identical. In this patch,

they are unified into one, adopting to:

1) The most accurate name, to avoid misuse.

2) The simplest signature, as IdentityManager isn't really needed to

achieve what the function needs to achieve.



TODOs have been added to track future work about revisiting if the

existing calling sites need to be migrated to more future-proof

functions.

entry.title: Add infrastructure to maintain the type used to fill an AutofilledField
entry.content:
Currently, Autofill only uses the classified type of a field in order to

fill it. In the future, this might change and we might sometimes

fallback to other types in case the classified type doesn't lead to a

successful filling.



In that case, `AutofillField::overall_type_` stops representing

accurately the filling state of the field, which might be needed by

other components.



This CL:

- Adds an `autofilled_type_` optional data member to AutofillField

tracking the type used to fill that field by Autofill.

- Adds logic to retrieve this information from the cache since this

information does not come from the renderer and hence newly built

AutofillFields cannot assign it.

- Adds logic to maintain history of that data member so that Undo

operations keeps this information consistent with the other states of

the field.

- Adds minimal logic to set this type whenever a field is autofilled.



Logic that will compute fallback types is out of scope of this CL.



This CL is a no-op.

entry.title: Revert^2 "Use the built-in Cronet telemetry stack"
entry.content:
This reverts commit e0d51530c73028dbdb7799a901adf00f1448665c.



Reason for revert: re-landing following https://crrev.com/c/5040785



Original change's description:

> Revert "Use the built-in Cronet telemetry stack"

>

> This reverts commit 3edea021bad8fdafebc2d11fb9bdc0266ce6d0e3.

>

> Reason for revert: Needed for another revert: https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5041483

>

> Bug: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1503204

>

> Original change's description:

> > Use the built-in Cronet telemetry stack

> >

> > Before this CL, Cronet expected to be shipped with a CronetLoggerImpl

> > class that lives outside of Chromium:

> >

> > - In the case of AOSP Cronet, that class would be built from AOSP along

> > with the rest of Cronet;

> > - In the case of Cronet embedded in Google 1P apps and Google Play

> > Services it would be built from an internal Google repo and the

> > resulting compiled class would be injected into the Cronet JAR at APK

> > build time;

> > - In any other cases (e.g. Maven) the class would not be present at

> > all.

> >

> > The above setup is extremely contrived and requires maintaining an

> > API/ABI boundary across 3 different repos, making this code very painful

> > to maintain. We have to juggle between all these repos every time we

> > make any changes to telemetry atom schemas, which is something we expect

> > to do somewhat regularly in the future. This is not sustainable.

> >

> > This CL simplifies the whole setup by making Cronet use the telemetry

> > code that was recently imported from AOSP into Chromium for this

> > purpose. From this point on, the entire telemetry logic lives in

> > Chromium and can be maintained just like the rest of Cronet code in the

> > normal way.

> >

> > The AOSP and internal code that attempts to inject a CronetLoggerImpl

> > class will have no effect after this CL - that code will become dead and

> > we should clean it up as soon as this commit makes it to these repos.

> >

> > The only downside of this change is that the atom definition still lives

> > elsewhere - the source of truth for that is in an internal Google

> > repo since the code that consumes the telemetry data is Google-internal.

> > The CronetStatsLog code is supposed to be autogenerated at build time

> > from the atom definition, but the relevant code generator only exists in

> > AOSP (under the name "stats-log-api-gen") and in the internal repo - it

> > does not exist in Chromium. So, for now, we'll have to run the code

> > generator manually and then manually copy its output over to Chromium,

> > every time we change atom definitions. This is not ideal, but that's a

> > small price to pay for the massive simplification that this CL brings.

> > Eventually we should solve this by having the atom proto definition in

> > Chromium (ideally autosynced from the internal repo) and then

> > autogenerate the logging code from it at build time in Chromium.

entry.title: [a11y] Move some of serialization pipeline from RAI to cache.
entry.content:
This CL aims to start moving some of the code path starting from HandleAXEvent to ScheduleImmediateAXUpdate over to cache side. The old code is still left in RAI for legacy support.



The aim is to eventually delete the code from RAI side, and then RAI would only be called from ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents to AXReadyCallback.



----------------------------

Details (only explaining post-lifecyle mode):

Before this CL, a11y events (kind of) go like this: AXObjectCacheImpl::PostPlatformNotification -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::HandleAXEvent which also calls AXObjectCacheImpl::AddPendingEvent --> RenderAccessibilityImpl::ScheduleImmediateAXUpdate -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleAXUpdate --> AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback



Note that -> doesn't mean direct calls. Some calls in the middle may have been skipped. The CL prevents these excessively unnecessary calls in between RAI (RenderAccessibilityImpl) and AXObjectCacheImpl. The calls now go like this (again kinda): AXObjectCacheImpl::PostPlatformNotification -> AXObjectCacheImpl::AddEventToSerializationQueue -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleImmediateSerialization -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleAXUpdate -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback



Notice how RAI is only called at the very end. Of course, to make this possible many of the side logic had to be moved too like the delaying code that used to be AXReadyCallback is now at AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents.



This image describes the above: https://i.imgur.com/U3tODTX.png

What the CL achieves is moving the code in the blue square over to the left-hand side, thus making the code stay in AXObjectCache longer and only move to RAI at RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback. The serialization delay is moved to ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents.



----------------------------

Legacy scheduling mode (as opposed to post-lifecycle serialization) still uses the old code which goes back and forth between RAI and AXObjectCache. The reason they were not moved as well is that legacy mode will get removed eventually anyway. When legacy mode is removed, we can safely remove the old code from RAI.



----------------------------

Also, with the cleaner code, it'll be feasible to change the scheduling logic further to limit some events like scrolling. Scrolling improvements discussed here https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fBK1BBrG8souqZpyv7q_3kxCYF1IYoXNPXmoVL7X8Gk/edit#heading=h.uo8ebdp7cxl



----------------------------

entry.title: Use all_dependent_configs to propagate linker directives for Rust tests.
entry.content:
The current test templates try to look for direct Rust dependencies and

ensure any .rlibs defining tests are pulled into the final binary by

forcing the whole archive to be included.



However, the test template cannot distinguish between Rust and non-Rust

dependencies, so building a tests containing Rust sources will actually

include command-line arguments to include the whole archive for

dependencies that aren't Rust at all, and do not even have a .rlib file.



In addition:

- the Windows linker (lld-link in Chrome) errors out if a non-existent

path is used with '/WHOLEARCHIVE:'

- this logic does not encapsulate transitive dependencies (e.g. if a

unit test depends on a GN group that contains Rust static libraries

with tests)



Rather than the test templates trying to fix up linking ex-post-facto,

this CL propagates required linking directives upwards through the build

graph by using all_dependent_configs. To avoid force including *all*

testonly static libs, this CL also re-introduces the use of the

`is_gtest_unittests` GN variable for `rust_static_library`. Only targets

that specify `is_gtest_unittests = true` will propagate a linker config

to include the whole archive of the .rlib.



Finally, to avoid issues with #[gtest(...)] static initializers being

silently dropped, the proc macro now errors out if a Rust target tries

to use the proc macro without setting `is_gtest_unittests = true` in its

GN target.

entry.title: [ChromeSigninIntercept] Fix avatar toolbar button showing name bug
entry.content:
As a result of b:301386027, the avatar toolbar button was sometimes blinking back and forth between displaying the profile name and not.

This was due to a logic error which was caused through the removal of

the enum value IdentityAnimationState::kWaitingForImage.

The CL adds the value and its check again.

With this, `IdentityAnimationState::kWaitingForImage` is only set in

`OnUserIdentityChanged`. Checking this state before showing the

animation ensures it is only shown if the user identity has changed.



Issue: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1503715

entry.title: Reland "Add SyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings to field trial config"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit bfe9bb7ec091d71d6925526098f9d74fd0cb048a



The CL was reverted (crrev.com/c/5046251) because the test failed on

in the browser_tests_no_field_trial target. As the name suggest, in

this (apparently existing) target, the field trial config and hence

SyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings remained disabled. The test however

enabled SyncEnableContactInfoDataTypeInTransportMode, leading to a

feature combination that in practice is not possible (

SyncEnableContactInfoDataTypeInTransportMode is conditioned on and will

be launched prior to SyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings).



This caused the test to fail, because as of crrev.com/c/5023899:

- `syncing_or_addresses_in_transport_mode` is true

- `has_autofill_sync_type` is false, since AUTOFILL_PROFILE is

not running (and not able to run) in transport mode.

Consequently, `syncing_or_addresses_in_transport_mode &&

!has_autofill_sync_type` became true, preventing credit card server

saves.



This CL fixes this problem by explicitly enabling both features in the

test in question.

entry.title: Revert "Deflake and reenable `ContentScriptViaScriptingApiWhileIdle` test."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 8f21a9e763ea281e391e2d7230a591bbcb9ef6d6.



Reason for revert: This test start failing consistently on https://ci.chromium.org/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Tests%20%28dbg%29%281%29 starting from https://ci.chromium.org/ui/b/8763769311537890929



Original change's description:

> Deflake and reenable `ContentScriptViaScriptingApiWhileIdle` test.

>

> The

> `DynamicScriptsTrackerBrowserTest.ContentScriptViaScriptingApiWhileIdle`

> test injects a content script at `document_idle` time. The test has

> been flakily timing out while waiting until the content script signals

> that is has been run (test logs from the bots show that the test was

> timing out during the `catcher.GetNextResult()` call).

>

> Based on reading the code it seems that:

>

> * The test properly waits for `DidFinishNavigation` for the navigation

> in the main frame.

> * The test properly controls the timing of the `onload` event for one of

> the subframes. The affected subframe is one of two subframes and the

> `ControllableHttpResponse` somewhat randomly catches one or the other.

> This is okay though - the `onload` event won't happen until *both*

> subframes have finished navigating.

>

> Based on the above, it seems that the content script should indeed get

> injected at `document_idle` time - after the `onload` event. Based on

> reading additional test code, it seems that the problem is that the

> content script *also* tries to wait for the `onload` event - this

> doesn't take into the account that this event might have already been

> raised.

>

> Based on the above this CL:

>

> * Attempts to speculatively fix the flakiness, by removing the

> `window.onload = function()` part of the content script

> * Removes the secondary and ultimately unnecessary test assertions

> around `document.readyState` (which changes around `onload` event)

> * Reenables the test

> * Adds additional `console.log` statements to the content script

> to help with diagnosing any remaining flakiness (if any; we

> speculatively assume that the test should not be flaky going forward).

>

entry.title: [Files]: Separating callback from other parameters.
entry.content:
RecentSource uses an approach where parameters given to GetRecentFiles

are stored in the optional field. That field is reset when the recent

source is done with collecting files. If it is done because the scan

finished, this is fine. If it is done because the timeout occurred, it

is possible that whoever holds to those params gets a null pointer,

which causes a crash.



This CL moves the callback argument out of params. This was what caused

the params to be forced to be move-only type. By moving callback out we

can make the params a copyable object. Thus early termination of the

slow will not empty the params for stragglers.

entry.title: vaapi: Disable VA-API on NVIDIA GPUs by default
entry.content:
NVIDIA has two known VA-API drivers for its GPUs: vdpau-driver and

nvidia-vaapi-driver.

- vdpau-driver is less maintained and can sometimes cause crashes.[1][2]

- nvidia-vaapi-driver does not support Chromium.[3][4]



This CL skips the 'nvidia-drm' device to disable loading VA-API drivers

on NVIDIA GPUs by default. This can be re-enabled by adding

`--enable-features=VaapiOnNvidiaGPUs` switch.



[1] https://cgit.freedesktop.org/vaapi/vdpau-driver

[2] crbug.com/1466825

[3] https://github.com/elFarto/nvidia-vaapi-driver/tree/v0.0.10#chrome

[4] crbug.com/1478925

entry.title: Mention the git longpaths support for Windows
entry.content:
By default git is constrained to the 260-character MAX_PATH limitation

on Windows. However this limitation can be configured away with this

command:



git config --global core.longpaths true



This is useful when cloning a repo that contains long paths, or if your

repo root has a longer path than expected.



Trivia: even with this configured the longest repo root path is around

210 characters. Any longer than that and "fatal: '$GIT_DIR' too big"

will be hit.



This issue was first hit and was initially tested with

"fetch infra_internal" but could hit elsewhere.



Testing has confirmed that this config setting lets git handle repos

and repo base paths that it otherwise fails on. Setting the

LongPathsEnabled registry key, in contrast, does not work.
